Thanks for your suggestions Kirk.

I know there is a lot of controversy and debate over why bloat exists in GP.
One explanation I have heard that makes a lot of sense to me is that
evolution is increasing the amount of neutral/irrelevant code in GP to
reduce its effective mutation rate (the relevant code becomes less likely to
be hit the more neutral code there is, as long as the mutation rate is
genomic and not per-site). Might that pressure also exist in NEAT?

A complicating factor in NEAT is speciation. Are there extra incentives to
be different from your neighbors to gain the protection of being in your own
species, which causes a pressure to be larger?

Just thinking out loud.

I do think that, at a minimum, a delete node mutation operator would help a
lot. It&#39;s been on my wish list for a long time, but I never seem to get
around to adding it.


