&gt;&gt;&gt; Jeff, first, if fitness is stagnant, then the system should be increasing
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt; average number of nodes (though not necessarily the number of nodes in
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt; champ). In a stagnant situation, you do not have information (i.e. a
&gt;&gt;&gt; gradient) suggesting which direction is right to go. Therefore, the most
&gt;&gt;&gt; principled response is to expand your options while never putting all
&gt;&gt; your
&gt;&gt;&gt; eggs in one basket. When fitness is stagnant, we cannot know if further
&gt;&gt;&gt; search within the currently dimensionality might eventually find a
&gt;&gt; solution,
&gt;&gt;&gt; or if the current dimensionality is insufficient and contains no solution
&gt;&gt; at
&gt;&gt;&gt; all. In the latter case, the number of nodes and connections would need
&gt;&gt; to
&gt;&gt;&gt; ascend to higher dimensionality. Because we do not know which case we are
&gt;&gt; in
&gt;&gt;&gt; when stagnation occurs, the best idea is to try both: Some species start
&gt;&gt;&gt; arriving with bigger networks while others keep searching in the same old
&gt;&gt;&gt; spaces. Thus, we would expect the *range* of sizes to increase along with
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt; average size.
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; Your situation with nondeterminism is probably somewhat similar, causing
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt; average size of solutions to go up because of stagnation. However,
&gt;&gt; because
&gt;&gt;&gt; the champion will keep changing with the randomized evaluation, you will
&gt;&gt;&gt; observe this phenomenon in the champion itself. The more noisy it is, the
&gt;&gt;&gt; more it is probably observable (i.e. because the more &quot;random&quot; it is who
&gt;&gt;&gt; happens to look best at any given time, in effect leading to a kind of
&gt;&gt;&gt; sampling of the population through the champion).
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; Of course, that may not be a complete explanation for the steep angle of
&gt;&gt; the
&gt;&gt;&gt; incline. I would guess that nondeterminism is also causing a general
&gt;&gt;&gt; unhealthiness about the evolutionary process overall. Nondeterminism is
&gt;&gt; highly
&gt;&gt;&gt; destructive to evolutionary algorithms. This issue is controversial (even
&gt;&gt;&gt; within my own group!) but my personal opinion is one should avoid
&gt;&gt;&gt; nondeterminism unless it is absolutely essential. For example, you can
&gt;&gt; choose
&gt;&gt;&gt; a random order of examples but then subject everyone to the same random
&gt;&gt; set -
&gt;&gt;&gt; a kind of &quot;deterministic randomness.&quot; Of course, you are banking on the
&gt;&gt;&gt; impartiality of randomness to give you maximal generality, but it will
&gt;&gt; often
&gt;&gt;&gt; be outweighed by its unhealthy side effects on the population. So I&#39;m
&gt;&gt;&gt; guessing that part of the phenomenon is just a side-effect of an
&gt;&gt; inconsistent
&gt;&gt;&gt; evaluation scheme leading to relative chaos.
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; There may also be more to it; it merits further investigation as well.
